# Bufferbloat Test Working Document

## Goal
Create a repeatable process in `netcheck.ps1` only to measure latency increase under traffic load (bufferbloat) and save results for review.

## Test concept
1. Measure baseline latency/jitter with no intentional traffic load.
2. Generate sustained downstream traffic load.
3. Re-measure latency/jitter during load.
4. Compare baseline vs loaded average RTT and jitter.

## Prerequisites
- Windows PowerShell 5.1+
- `netcheck.ps1` in repo root
- Internet access
- Write access to `C:\temp\netcheck\`
- iPerf binary available at `C:\temp\iperf-3.1.3-win64\iperf3.exe` (auto-downloaded by `-SpeedTest` job if missing)

## Step 1: Baseline jitter run (no load)
```powershell
.\netcheck.ps1 -Jitter -JitterSamples 20 -JitterIntervalMs 1000
```

Record these baseline fields per target:
- `AvgMs`
- `JitterMs`
- `LossPercent`

## Step 2: Loaded run (jitter during iPerf traffic)
Run jitter and speed test together so jitter is captured while iPerf traffic is active:
```powershell
.\netcheck.ps1 -Jitter -SpeedTest -JitterSamples 20 -JitterIntervalMs 1000
```

This uses the existing `-SpeedTest` job (iPerf) as the traffic generator.

## Step 3: Interpret
Use this rough grading by delta from baseline:
- `0-5 ms`: Excellent
- `6-20 ms`: Good
- `21-40 ms`: Fair
- `>40 ms`: Poor (likely bufferbloat under load)

Compare:
- `Loaded AvgMs - Baseline AvgMs`
- `Loaded JitterMs - Baseline JitterMs`
- Any increase in `LossPercent`

## Output files
- Baseline/loaded jitter: `C:\temp\netcheck\Jitter.txt`
- iPerf traffic run details: `C:\temp\netcheck\Speed test.txt`

## Quick validation command
```powershell
Get-Content C:\temp\netcheck\Jitter.txt
Get-Content "C:\temp\netcheck\Speed test.txt"
```

Expected output contains:
- header with date/time
- target list
- table with `Target`, `Sent`, `Received`, `LossPercent`, `MinMs`, `AvgMs`, `MaxMs`, `JitterMs`, `Status`
- speed test log lines showing iPerf target/port and completion or error status
